    <item>
      <title>Llamafile</title>
      <link>http://localhost:1313/blog/llamafile/</link>
      <pubDate>Tue, 24 Jun 2025 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>http://localhost:1313/blog/llamafile/</guid>
      <description>&lt;figure&gt;&#xA;    &#xA;        &lt;img src=&#34;https://cdn-uploads.huggingface.co/production/uploads/64a523ba1ed90082dafde3d3/kJrkxofwOp-89uYFe0EBb.png&#34; alt=&#34;llamafile banner&#34; /&gt;&#xA;    &#xA;&lt;/figure&gt;&#xA;&#xA;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;Last week, I stumbled upon &#xA;&lt;a href=&#34;https://github.com/Mozilla-Ocho/llamafile&#34; target=&#34;_blank&#34; rel=&#34;noopener&#34;&gt;llamafile&lt;/a&gt;&#xA;. It&amp;rsquo;s a file format developed by &#xA;&lt;a href=&#34;https://www.mozilla.org/en-US/&#34; target=&#34;_blank&#34; rel=&#34;noopener&#34;&gt;Mozilla&lt;/a&gt;&#xA; that stores the weights and code of &#xA;&lt;a href=&#34;https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Large_language_model&#34; target=&#34;_blank&#34; rel=&#34;noopener&#34;&gt;LLMs&lt;/a&gt;&#xA; as pre-compiled &#xA;&lt;a href=&#34;https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Binary_code&#34; target=&#34;_blank&#34; rel=&#34;noopener&#34;&gt;binary machine code&lt;/a&gt;&#xA;. What this means is that you can run a llamafile on &lt;em&gt;any&lt;/em&gt; computer without installing &lt;em&gt;anything&lt;/em&gt; else.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;Actually, I need to qualify the &amp;ldquo;run on any computer&amp;rdquo; statement a bit. Llamafiles can run on any computer running &#xA;&lt;a href=&#34;https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Microsoft_Windows&#34; target=&#34;_blank&#34; rel=&#34;noopener&#34;&gt;Windows&lt;/a&gt;&#xA;, &#xA;&lt;a href=&#34;https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/MacOS&#34; target=&#34;_blank&#34; rel=&#34;noopener&#34;&gt;MacOS&lt;/a&gt;&#xA;, &#xA;&lt;a href=&#34;https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Linux&#34; target=&#34;_blank&#34; rel=&#34;noopener&#34;&gt;Linux&lt;/a&gt;&#xA;, &#xA;&lt;a href=&#34;https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/FreeBSD&#34; target=&#34;_blank&#34; rel=&#34;noopener&#34;&gt;FreeBSD&lt;/a&gt;&#xA;, &#xA;&lt;a href=&#34;https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/NetBSD&#34; target=&#34;_blank&#34; rel=&#34;noopener&#34;&gt;NetBSD&lt;/a&gt;&#xA;, or &#xA;&lt;a href=&#34;https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/OpenBSD&#34; target=&#34;_blank&#34; rel=&#34;noopener&#34;&gt;OpenBSD&lt;/a&gt;&#xA;. The computer needs to have a &#xA;&lt;a href=&#34;https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/AMD&#34; target=&#34;_blank&#34; rel=&#34;noopener&#34;&gt;64-bit AMD processor&lt;/a&gt;&#xA;, an &#xA;&lt;a href=&#34;https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_Intel_processors&#34; target=&#34;_blank&#34; rel=&#34;noopener&#34;&gt;Intel processor newer than 2006&lt;/a&gt;&#xA;, a &#xA;&lt;a href=&#34;https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ARM_architecture_family&#34; target=&#34;_blank&#34; rel=&#34;noopener&#34;&gt;64-bit ARM processor&lt;/a&gt;&#xA;, or an &#xA;&lt;a href=&#34;https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Apple_silicon&#34; target=&#34;_blank&#34; rel=&#34;noopener&#34;&gt;Apple Silicon&lt;/a&gt;&#xA; processor. You&amp;rsquo;ll also need a non-trivial amount of RAM: 4 gigabtyes at minimum. These requirements are very lax, and your computer probably meets those specifications if it was manufactured less than a decade ago.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>A website about Salt</title>
      <link>http://localhost:1313/blog/saltassociation/</link>
      <pubDate>Wed, 11 Jun 2025 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>http://localhost:1313/blog/saltassociation/</guid>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;Salt is my favorite mineral. It&amp;rsquo;s easily the most delicious (Sitenote: despite its name, &#xA;&lt;a href=&#34;https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cinnabar&#34; target=&#34;_blank&#34; rel=&#34;noopener&#34;&gt;Cinnabar&lt;/a&gt;&#xA; is actually not tasty at all), it &#xA;&lt;a href=&#34;https://salinity.oceansciences.org/media/ed_image_81_salt_crystal.jpg&#34; target=&#34;_blank&#34; rel=&#34;noopener&#34;&gt;looks awesome under an electron microscope&lt;/a&gt;&#xA;, and it&amp;rsquo;s so abundant that it forms colossal salt caverns and vast salt flats.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&#xA;&#xA;&#xA;&#xA;&#xA;&#xA;&#xA;&#xA;&lt;figure&gt;&#xA;    &#xA;        &lt;img src=&#34;https://149576366.v2.pressablecdn.com/wp-content/uploads/Salar_de_Uyuni_in_Bolivia.jpg&#34; alt=&#34;A large, textured salt flat with polygonal patterns stretches to a distant mountain range under a vibrant orange and blue sunset sky&#34; /&gt;&#xA;    &#xA;&lt;/figure&gt;&#xA;&#xA;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;Yesterday (June 10, 2025), I discovered that the top result on Google Images for &#xA;&lt;a href=&#34;https://www.google.com/search?q=salt&amp;#43;flat&amp;amp;udm=2&#34; target=&#34;_blank&#34; rel=&#34;noopener&#34;&gt;&amp;ldquo;Salt Flat&amp;rdquo;&lt;/a&gt;&#xA; is this beautiful photo of the &#xA;&lt;a href=&#34;https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Salar_de_Uyuni&#34; target=&#34;_blank&#34; rel=&#34;noopener&#34;&gt;Uyuni Salt Flat&lt;/a&gt;&#xA;. It is currently set as my desktop wallpaper.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>A language written in fish</title>
      <link>http://localhost:1313/blog/tsevhu/</link>
      <pubDate>Sat, 26 Apr 2025 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>http://localhost:1313/blog/tsevhu/</guid>
      <description>&lt;figure&gt;&#xA;    &#xA;        &lt;img src=&#34;http://localhost:1313/media/tsevhu_poem.svg&#34; alt=&#34;A poem written in Tsevhu&#34; /&gt;&#xA;    &#xA;&lt;/figure&gt;&#xA;&#xA;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;&#xA;&lt;a href=&#34;https://conlang.fandom.com/wiki/Tsevhu&#34; target=&#34;_blank&#34; rel=&#34;noopener&#34;&gt;Tsevhu&lt;/a&gt;&#xA; is a &#xA;&lt;a href=&#34;https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Constructed_language&#34; target=&#34;_blank&#34; rel=&#34;noopener&#34;&gt;constructed language&lt;/a&gt;&#xA; which is written with fish-like glyphs rather than Latin letters.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;Disclaimer: I only sort of understand how Tsevhu works, so my explanation of the grammar is probably partially inaccurate.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;h2 id=&#34;translation&#34;&gt;Translation&lt;/h2&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;According to the inventor of Tsevhu, Koa Vhukva, the fishes in the image above translate to:&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;blockquote&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;When I traveled the world,&lt;/em&gt;&lt;br&gt;&#xA;&lt;em&gt;I traveled lonely.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;br&gt;&#xA;&lt;em&gt;A desolate landscape&lt;/em&gt;&lt;br&gt;&#xA;&lt;em&gt;scraped my view,&lt;/em&gt;&lt;br&gt;&#xA;&lt;em&gt;A dead thing to keep me company.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;br&gt;&#xA;&lt;em&gt;I wandered because&lt;/em&gt;&lt;br&gt;&#xA;&lt;em&gt;it was the only thing left to do.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;br&gt;&#xA;&lt;em&gt;When I found you,&lt;/em&gt;&lt;br&gt;&#xA;&lt;em&gt;you were in stasis,&lt;/em&gt;&lt;br&gt;&#xA;&lt;em&gt;frozen for more&lt;/em&gt;&lt;br&gt;&#xA;&lt;em&gt;than a century&lt;/em&gt;&lt;br&gt;&#xA;&lt;em&gt;asleep, delicate in all your graces,&lt;/em&gt;&lt;br&gt;&#xA;&lt;em&gt;and I felt all my years&lt;/em&gt;&lt;br&gt;&#xA;&lt;em&gt;telling me to wake you.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>The Waterman Butterfly</title>
      <link>http://localhost:1313/blog/waterman/</link>
      <pubDate>Fri, 25 Apr 2025 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>http://localhost:1313/blog/waterman/</guid>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;I&amp;rsquo;m willing to bet that you&amp;rsquo;ve seen a map of the Earth before.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;But I doubt that you&amp;rsquo;ve seen this one.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&#xA;&#xA;&#xA;&#xA;&#xA;&#xA;&#xA;&#xA;&lt;figure&gt;&#xA;    &#xA;        &lt;img src=&#34;http://localhost:1313/media/waterman.webp&#34; alt=&#34;The Waterman Butterfly&#34; /&gt;&#xA;    &#xA;&lt;/figure&gt;&#xA;&#xA;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;This is the &#xA;&lt;a href=&#34;https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Waterman_butterfly_projection&#34; target=&#34;_blank&#34; rel=&#34;noopener&#34;&gt;Waterman Butterfly projection&lt;/a&gt;&#xA;, an alternative map projection developed by Steve Waterman.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;In my experience, most people&amp;rsquo;s first reaction to seeing the Waterman is &lt;em&gt;&amp;ldquo;Wow, that&amp;rsquo;s so pretty!&amp;rdquo;&lt;/em&gt;, followed by &lt;em&gt;&amp;ldquo;Wow, what a goofy and impractical map!&amp;rdquo;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;However, I think that the Waterman is a genuinely useful projection, even with its drawbacks.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
